Welcome back to Wall Power. I=E2=80=99m Marion Maneker,
just popping in to introduce tonight=E2=80=99s email by Julie Brener Davich=
=2E=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I was asked a few months ago (you know who you are=E2=80=A6) whether we cou=
ld provide more coverage of the gallery scene. Since Julie has written some=
 excellent gallery previews, I thought we would try out an occasional Frida=
y email offering a survey of what=E2=80=99s on view. I suspect that you=E2=
=80=99ll find this to be a useful guide to
seeing a few shows on Saturday or during the week.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Going to see art doesn=E2=80=99t have to be a big expedition=E2=80=94just s=
top by a gallery on your way to do other things. If you see a great show, e=
mail Julie at JDavich@puck.news ( jdavich@puck.news?utm_campaign=3DWall+Pow=
er+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F24%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%=
281%2F24%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_ter=
m=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) and let her know what you think. Now, Julie=E2=80=
=99s going to take you around Manhattan.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But first, a quick stop in Paris=E2=80=A6

Julie Brener Davich
Julie Brener Davich

=E2=80=8A

Paris Curates Fashion
---------------------

This weekend marks the opening of the sumptuous Louvre Couture. Art and
Fashion: Statement Pieces. The exhibition features more than 100 different =
looks and accessories from the past 65 years, organized into seven historic=
al periods, from Byzantium and the Middle Ages to the 19th century, on disp=
lay throughout the museum=E2=80=99s 100,000 square feet of decorative arts =
galleries.

=C2=A0

Each item resonates with the history of decorative arts=E2=80=94the evolvin=
g styles, exquisite craftsmanship,
elaborate ornamentation, etcetera. To wit: You=E2=80=99ll see a pattern fro=
m an 18th century Andr=C3=A9-Charles Boulle armoire, reimagined as brocaded=
 silk damask and Lesage embroidery in a 1990 Givenchy evening trouser suit.=
 The 45 participating brands range from Dries Van Noten to Versace to Vivie=
nne Westwood, with about two-thirds of them coming from Paris.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

This show marks the first time that
the Louvre, which does not have a permanent fashion collection, has staged =
a fashion exhibition. Surely its curators saw the success of the Met Costum=
e Institute=E2=80=99s annual exhibition and gala, with its infinite social =
impressions and celebrities climbing over one another to get invited. Anywa=
y, word from my partner Lauren Sherman in this week=E2=80=99s
Line Sheet ( https://puck.news/newsletter_content/kardashian-deal-flow-secr=
ets-sephora-sponcon-terry-richardsons-return-2/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-=
+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F24%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%=
2F24%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3D=
f6c60617da42abd12a ) is that fashion brands have snapped up around 30 table=
s for the gala scheduled for March 4, to kick off Fashion Week. I also hear=
 the museum has already achieved its =E2=82=AC1 million fundraising goal, w=
hich I think is rather unambitious considering a single table at the Met Ga=
la goes for $350,000=E2=80=94and the fact that, as
reported ( https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/louvre-director-memo-overc=
rowding-leaks-mona-lisa-1234730700/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS=
+%281%2F24%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F24%2F25%29=
&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42=
abd12a ) in ARTnews today, the Louvre=E2=80=99s infrastructure is literally=
 crumbling.

=C2=A0

The Louvre show, on view through July 21, is curated by senior heritage cur=
ator Olivier Gabet, who came to the museum just over two years ago from the=
 Mus=C3=A9e
des Arts D=C3=A9coratifs. Additional events include a live performance by B=
roadway producer and budding fashion icon Jordan Roth (son of real estate m=
ogul Steven Roth and Broadway producer Daryl Roth) on July 4, timed to cout=
ure season.

Dolce Gabbana exhibit

From Du C=C5=93ur =C3=A0 La Main, Dolce & Gabbana

Just down the Quai de Tuileries, at the Grand Palais, is the Dolce
& Gabbana exhibition, Du Coeur =C3=A0 la Main (=E2=80=9CFrom the Heart to t=
he Hand=E2=80=9D). It=E2=80=99s a second chance to catch the magic after th=
e show=E2=80=99s sold-out run in Milan last spring. The presentation focuse=
s on the duo=E2=80=99s output since 2012, when they began doing Alta Moda=
=E2=80=94the Italian term for haute couture. Ten immersive rooms filled wit=
h opulent clothing, accessories, and decorative arts take visitors on a gra=
nd tour of Italian culture and architecture: columnar dresses in an ancient=
 temple,
sequined suits in a Byzantine basilica, brightly painted fabrics among Sici=
lian tiles.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Since Dolce & Gabbana is a luxury brand that also sells ready-to-wear, the =
exhibition is a genius customer acquisition and relationship-building tool,=
 especially given its proven success in Milan. The show is on view only thr=
ough March 31.

Meanwhile, back in New York=E2=80=A6

A Nevelson Revival & New York=E2=80=99s Winter Show

***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
*******
A Nevelson Revival & New York=E2=80=99s Winter Show ( https://puck.news/a-l=
ouise-nevelson-revival-new-yorks-winter-art-shows/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Powe=
r+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F24%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2=
81%2F24%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=
=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
*******

Louise Nevelson is having a moment, with a show at Pace Gallery and jewelry=
 by
Celine; meanwhile at the Park Avenue Armory, a trove of treasures gets fete=
d.

Julie Brener Davich ( https://puck.news/author/juliedavich/?utm_campaign=3D=
Wall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F24%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSC=
RIBERS+%281%2F24%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io=
&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Julie Brener Davich ( https://puck.news/author/juliedavich/?utm_campaign=3D=
Wall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F24%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSC=
RIBERS+%281%2F24%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io=
&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Arne Glimcher, the founder of Pace Gallery, was an upstart
21-year-old when he first encountered Louise Nevelson=E2=80=99s work in the=
 1960 MoMA show 16 Americans. Nevelson, for her part, was already 60 years =
old when legendary MoMA curator Dorothy Miller asked her to participate in =
the exhibition alongside Jasper Johns, Robert Rauschenberg, and Frank Stell=
a. For that show, Nevelson created Dawn=E2=80=99s Wedding Feast=E2=80=94an =
entire gallery filled with her signature
sculptures and wall pieces made from wooden scraps and painted a solid colo=
r (in this instance white, but more frequently in her career, black).=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Glimcher was enamored. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d never seen anything like that b=
efore or since,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CI knew she was the progenitor=
 of installation art in America.=E2=80=9D Nevelson took detritus from the c=
ity streets and transformed them into architecture. She eradicated their hi=
story as
individual objects, elevating the banal into something sublime=E2=80=94in f=
act, in 1975, she would be commissioned to adorn a chapel at Saint Peter=E2=
=80=99s Church.

Louise Nevelson: Shadow Dance, New York. (Photo: Courtesy of Pace Gallery)

Glimcher called up Nevelson=E2=80=99s gallerist at the time, Martha Jackson=
, and got
the go-ahead to mount a show of her work at his new Boston gallery. =E2=80=
=9CI think my sincerity was captivating,=E2=80=9D he laughed. He rented a U=
-Haul, packed all the sculptures with cardboard in between, and drove them =
up to Massachusetts. The show resulted in Nevelson=E2=80=99s first signific=
ant sales.

Nevelson Finds a Home
---------------------

After leaving Jackson, Nevelson did a brief stint at Sidney
Janis Gallery, where she had one show in which nothing sold. Glimcher then =
staged a major coup=E2=80=94paying off Nevelson=E2=80=99s debt to Janis and=
 bringing her to his own new gallery in New York, where she remained until =
her death in 1988. =E2=80=9CShe was very much the backbone of the gallery,=
=E2=80=9D he said. Over that 25-year period, Glimcher mounted about a dozen=
 solo shows of her work, and then as many posthumously. The most recent sho=
w, Shadow Dance, curated by Glimcher and including
several works from his personal collection, is on view through March 1 at P=
ace=E2=80=99s New York gallery.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The show comprises almost entirely works from the late 1960s to the 1980s, =
some of which have never been shown. Oliver Shultz, Pace=E2=80=99s chief cu=
rator, described these later works as =E2=80=9Cmore transgressive and exube=
rant.=E2=80=9D Not only are they more curvilinear than her earlier works, b=
ut they
also have some identifiable objects, like headboards and chairs.

=C2=A0

About half of the works in the show are for sale, with the sculptural piece=
s ranging in price from $375,000 to several million. Nevelson had a strong =
market during her lifetime, Glimcher told me, but most of her buyers were m=
useums that could accommodate the monumental scale of her pieces. That mean=
s there are few works available, especially earlier ones.
There=E2=80=99s never been a hugely significant work of hers offered at auc=
tion, where her record is only $1.35 million. But Glimcher said several pie=
ces have sold privately for up to $4 million. In general, her white pieces =
are more prized than the black ones.

The Eclipse and the Comeback
----------------------------

After Nevelson died, =E2=80=9Cher works went into eclipse,=E2=80=9D said Sh=
ultz. She was a
flamboyant, instantly recognizable personality=E2=80=94a style influencer, =
if you will=E2=80=94and became indistinguishable from her work. =E2=80=9CWh=
en people stopped seeing her,=E2=80=9D continued Shultz, =E2=80=9Cthey stop=
ped seeing the works.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But a revival is underway. In 2022, the Louise Nevelson Foundation, founded=
 in 2005 by her granddaughter, Maria Nevelson, organized a show of 60 works=
 at the Venice Biennale. The
event=E2=80=94championed, of course, by Glimcher=E2=80=94celebrated the 60t=
h anniversary of Nevelson representing the U.S. in the 1962 Biennale.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

More museums are bringing their Nevelson works out of storage; the Centre P=
ompidou-Metz in Lorraine, France, is staging a solo exhibition of her works=
 this fall. But there is perhaps no greater sign of an artist=E2=80=99s inc=
reasing visibility than a fashion brand wanting to bask
in their aura. So it=E2=80=99s notable that the Celine Artist Jewelry Progr=
am, headed by artistic director Hedi Slimane, is selling two limited-editio=
n necklaces ( https://www.celine.com/en-us/celine-maison-de-couture/collabo=
rations/collaboration-nevelson/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%28=
1%2F24%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F24%2F25%29&utm=
_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd1=
2a ) informed by Nevelson=E2=80=99s own jewelry designs for $4,500 (silver)=
 and $5,300 (gold). Gallerist Didier Haspeslagh, who specializes in jewelry=
 made by artists,
told me that most female artists eschew making jewelry for fear of being se=
en as too feminine. =E2=80=9COnly the really strong, successful female arti=
sts make jewelry,=E2=80=9D he said.

=C2=A0

In town for a couple days? There are a couple other excellent gallery shows=
 that should be on your agenda=E2=80=A6

Elsewhere in
Galleries
------------

Katie Paterson at James Cohan: On view in Tribeca through February 22 are w=
orks by
Scottish artist Katie Paterson. Inspired by a trip to Iceland when she was =
a student, Paterson focuses her art on =E2=80=9Cdeep time,=E2=80=9D or the =
history of Earth over millions of years. Each work in her =E2=80=9CO=E2=80=
=9D series is a solid circle that looks painted, but is actually made from =
materials like the ashes of 10,000 trees and salts collected from evaporate=
d oceans.=C2=A0

Katie Paterson,=C2=A0There Is Another Sky=C2=A0(Photo: Courtesy of Katie Pa=
terson &
James Cohan)

Other works include a handblown hourglass containing stardust, and a large
embroidery on linen depicting 352 extinct plants. In the back gallery is a =
10.5-foot glass column made from desert sands across the earth, similar to =
the columns she used in her installation Mirage (2023) for Apple=E2=80=99s =
campus in Cupertino. The works, many of which come in multiple editions, ra=
nge in price from =C2=A38,500 to =C2=A3225,000.

=C2=A0

Etel Adnan at White Cube: Meanwhile, uptown, a show of works by the
late Lebanon-born artist and writer Etel Adnan is on display at White Cube.=
 The international art world discovered her less than 15 years ago, and wit=
h 45 of her top 50 auction prices achieved after her death in fall 2021, it=
=E2=80=99s safe to say her market is on a steep upward trajectory. She=E2=
=80=99s primarily a colorist known for petite canvases that evoke a sense o=
f place, but this exhibition brings together works across various media, in=
cluding a large-scale, tiled ceramic wall piece;
leporellos (handheld books folded accordion-like); and colorful tapestries.=
 Both the ceramic work and the tapestries were created posthumously from th=
e artist=E2=80=99s decades-old designs.=C2=A0

Etel Adnan,=C2=A0This Beautiful Light, 2025 (Photo: Frankie Tyska/Courtesy =
of
White Cube)

Given the explosion in prices for her works, it makes sense that White Cube=
 would want to feed
the hungry market. The tapestries, available for $180,000 each in editions =
of three, were produced by the French weaver Pinton, which has also worked =
with Alexander Calder, Sonia Delaunay, and Fernand L=C3=A9ger. Their abilit=
y to replicate the look of brushstrokes using thread is uncanny. Marion and=
 I have the same favorite: the 75-inch-square D=C3=A9sert Ensoleill=C3=A9 1=
960s (2023).

Winter
Wonders
-------

If you want to stay out of the cold and see a lot of art in one concentrate=
d
place, head to the Armory on 68th Street. The Winter Show, which cast off t=
he mustiness of the word =E2=80=9CAntiques=E2=80=9D in its title several ye=
ars ago, opened last night with champagne, caviar, and visits from Michael =
Bloomberg, Nicky Hilton, and Martha Stewart. Unlike for-profit fairs, The W=
inter Show was established more than 70 years ago by East Side House Settle=
ment, a community-based organization in the Bronx, as a fundraising
event.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Almost 80 dealers from nine countries brought treasures ranging from silver=
 and jewelry to paintings and works on paper to furniture and ceramics. Som=
e of the leading gallerists in their respective fields are on hand, includi=
ng Koopman Rare Art for silver, Ronald Phillips Ltd. for English furniture,=
 Michele Beiny for ceramics, and Peter Finer for arms and
armor.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The fair is =E2=80=9Cvetted,=E2=80=9D which is a term I=E2=80=99ve never re=
ally questioned over my 20 years in the art and design field. It turns out,=
 as 18th century English antiques dealer Clinton Howell explained, the day =
before the fair opened to the public, the objects were examined by more tha=
n 120 specialists across 30 disciplines to confirm their authenticity, qual=
ity, and value, so buyers can have full
confidence in what they are buying.

The Winter Show, New York (Photo: Matt Borkowski/Courtesy of BFA.com)

The first booth I happened upon when I previewed the fair yesterday was tha=
t
of Michael Goedhuis, who specializes in Asian art. He shared with me the re=
surgence in interest in Japanese art, and showed me three rare 17th century=
 bronze flower vessels that he=E2=80=99s selling for $9,000 to $16,000. (Fr=
ancesco Goedhuis, his son, serves on Puck=E2=80=99s board of directors.) At=
 Finer=E2=80=99s arms-and-armor booth, I learned that half his clients are =
female. =E2=80=9CWeapons are functioning objects, but they=E2=80=99re also =
art,=E2=80=9D he explained, pointing to a rare
17th-18th century Mughal dagger with a jade, ruby, and gold handle carved i=
n the shape of a horse=E2=80=99s head.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Beiny, meanwhile, specializes in porcelain and ceramics. Up until 10 years =
ago that meant Meissen and S=C3=A8vres, but now he also deals in modern and=
 contemporary ceramics and glass by the likes of Michael Dickey and Jennife=
r McCurdy. In fact, the first red dot I saw
at the fair was at Beiny=E2=80=99s booth, for a purple copper glaze porcela=
in vase by Brother Thomas Bezanson. The most Instagrammable booth was that =
of first-time attendee Galerie Gmurzynska. The gallery brought a 6-foot-lon=
g wooden Tom Wesselmann sculpture of a smoking cigarette=E2=80=94a recurren=
t theme in the artist=E2=80=99s practice=E2=80=94priced just under $1 milli=
on.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The final booth that
caught my eye was that of Didier Ltd., which specializes in jewelry by arti=
sts. Capitalizing on the current market craze for Les Lalanne, the Didiers =
brought an impressive selection of designs by Claude Lalanne, including som=
e galvanized leaf pieces and a child=E2=80=99s gold-and-diamond =E2=80=9Cpa=
pillon=E2=80=9D bracelet purchased at Christie=E2=80=99s 2023 Rothschild sa=
le. The most remarkable object is a gold brooch cast from the lips of model=
 Veruschka, whose midriff was
also memorialized in gold by Yves Saint Laurent.

=C2=A0

The Winter Show is on view for 10 days, accompanied by a full slate of even=
ts and programming. Don=E2=80=99t miss my friend Christine Donahue Kavanagh=
 of Sotheby=E2=80=99s leading a panel discussion this Sunday afternoon abou=
t collection management and legacy planning.

=E2=80=8A

Endnotes=E2=80=A6
-----------

Thank you, Julie. If you liked having a gallery roundup, let me know by
replying to this email. If we get a good response, we=E2=80=99ll do more.=
=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I promised you more on the Sotheby=E2=80=99s 2024 results call that took pl=
ace Thursday morning. I=E2=80=99ll delve into that on Sunday. We=E2=80=99ll=
 also have results from the Jeff Beck guitar sale and Americana week, just =
to keep us all honest on the previews.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Till then,

M

