in-bottom:0px;">This weekend marks the opening of the sumptuous <em>Louvre =
Couture. Art and
Fashion: Statement Pieces</em>. The exhibition features more than 100 diffe=
rent looks and accessories from the past 65 years, organized into seven his=
torical periods, from Byzantium and the Middle Ages to the 19th century, on=
 display throughout the museum=E2=80=99s 100,000 square feet of decorative =
arts galleries.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Each item resonates with the history of=
 decorative arts=E2=80=94the evolving styles, exquisite craftsmanship,
elaborate ornamentation, etcetera. To wit: You=E2=80=99ll see a pattern fro=
m an 18th century <strong>Andr=C3=A9-Charles Boulle</strong> armoire, reima=
gined as brocaded silk damask and Lesage embroidery in a 1990 Givenchy even=
ing trouser suit. The 45 participating brands range from Dries Van Noten to=
 Versace to Vivienne Westwood, with about two-thirds of them coming from Pa=
ris.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">This show marks the first time that
the Louvre, which does not have a permanent fashion collection, has staged =
a fashion exhibition. Surely its curators saw the success of the Met Costum=
e Institute=E2=80=99s annual exhibition and gala, with its infinite social =
impressions and celebrities climbing over one another to get invited. Anywa=
y, word from my partner <strong>Lauren Sherman</strong> in this week=E2=80=
=99s
